Lineage — how Spark recovers from failure.

Spark does not replicate R-D-D data the way a file system like H-D-F-S does. Instead, it remembers the recipe — the sequence of transformations that produced each R-D-D. That recipe is called the lineage graph.

So what happens when a partition is lost, because an executor crashes or a machine dies? Spark replays just the relevant slice of the lineage, and rebuilds that one partition. It is cheap when the lineage is short, and expensive when the lineage is long. The resilience comes from the pure functions plus the lineage — not from keeping copies of the data.

This is also exactly why caching matters. Without cache, every action re-runs the full lineage, all the way from the source. So if you reuse an R-D-D in two different actions, you compute it twice. Caching, which we cover shortly, breaks that by materializing the R-D-D after the first action.
